JOHANNESBURG - Stats SA on Wednesday said the annual Consumer Price Inflation (CPI) was lower in February at 2.9% compared to the 3.2% recorded the previous month. The rate is the lowest since June last year when it stood at 2.2%. Stats SA has put the lower CPI reading in February down to several contributors including food and non-alcoholic beverages, which increased by 5.2% year on year. #CPI inflation was 2,9% in February 2021, down from 3,2% in January 2021. This is the lowest reading since June 2020 when the rate was 2,2%Listen here for more: https://t.co/vZnpSdPEL9#StatsSA #inflation pic.twitter.com/QTh4icS7j0  Housing and utilities increased by 2.6% and contributed a 0.6 percentage point. CPI measures the prices of goods and services consumed by South Africans and is used to calculate the inflation rate for the economy. The figures released on Wednesday morning reflect the CPI for all urban areas. Meanwhile, the provincial annual inflation rates were 2.7% in Gauteng and 3.3% in Mpumalanga and the North West. Download the Eyewitness News app to your iOS  or Android device.